docs.abstract: Regulators are clamping down on the credit bureau in the aftermath of the breach, which left 147 million people vulnerable.
docs.snippet: Regulators are clamping down on the credit bureau in the aftermath of the breach, which left 147 million people vulnerable.
docs.lead_paragraph: Equifax agreed to a number of data security rules under a consent order with eight state financial regulators that was announced on Wednesday, the latest regulatory response to the breach that allowed hackers to steal sensitive personal information on more than 147 million people.

headline.main: 8 States Impose New Rules on Equifax After Data Breach
headline.print_headline: 8 States Impose New Rules On Equifax for Data Breach

docs.abstract: A new law allows consumers to lift a security freeze without charge when they want to apply for a credit card or a car loan.
docs.snippet: A new law allows consumers to lift a security freeze without charge when they want to apply for a credit card or a car loan.
docs.lead_paragraph: People who froze their credit files before September may notice some changes when the time comes to thaw the files.

headline.main: So You’ve Frozen Your Credit Files. Here Are Tips on Unfreezing Them.
headline.print_headline: Froze Your Credit? How It Thaws Is Changing

docs.abstract: Mark Begor thinks Equifax can be the consumer-friendly credit bureau. So where are our free credit reports, automatic credit freezes for babies and consistent straight talk?
docs.snippet: Mark Begor thinks Equifax can be the consumer-friendly credit bureau. So where are our free credit reports, automatic credit freezes for babies and consistent straight talk?
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — A few years ago, Mark Begor checked his credit report, as befits a corporate executive with proper personal finance hygiene. It was filthy.

headline.main: The New Equifax Boss Wants to Make Amends. We Have Some Questions.

docs.abstract: Because of a high volume of requests, the agency said, it will not be able to offer $125, the upper limit of what was initially offered.
docs.snippet: Because of a high volume of requests, the agency said, it will not be able to offer $125, the upper limit of what was initially offered.
docs.lead_paragraph: Overwhelmed by requests from consumers seeking compensation related to the giant 2017 data breach at the credit bureau Equifax, the Federal Trade Commission is recommending that people accept free credit monitoring rather than cash.

headline.main: Skip Cash for Equifax Breach and Get Credit Monitoring, F.T.C. Tells Victims

docs.abstract: Consumers have a few options for dealing with the data breach settlement.
docs.snippet: Consumers have a few options for dealing with the data breach settlement.
docs.lead_paragraph: Equifax had one job — keep its vast trove of personal financial information on millions of Americans secure. In 2017, the company failed spectacularly at that job when a hack compromised the information of more than 147 million people.

headline.main: Equifax Doesn’t Want You to Get Your $125. Here’s What You Can Do.
headline.print_headline: What to Do to Get Justice From Equifax

docs.abstract: The free service started after Equifax’s huge breach in 2017. Consumer advocates suggest placing a security freeze — not a lock — on credit files.
docs.snippet: The free service started after Equifax’s huge breach in 2017. Consumer advocates suggest placing a security freeze — not a lock — on credit files.
docs.lead_paragraph: Consumers affected by Equifax’s huge data breach in 2017 may need to re-establish protections on their credit report if they “locked” their files as part of the company’s free credit-monitoring offer.

headline.main: Year of Free Credit Report Monitoring Is Ending. Here’s What to Do Now.
headline.print_headline: Free Credit ‘Lock’ Is Ending. What Now?

docs.abstract: After 145 million Americans’ financial information was exposed last year, some of them won cases against the credit reporting agency in local courts.
docs.snippet: After 145 million Americans’ financial information was exposed last year, some of them won cases against the credit reporting agency in local courts.
docs.lead_paragraph: Christina Bernstein’s check finally arrived last week: $7,440 from Equifax for her trouble.

headline.main: How a Few People Took Equifax to Small Claims Court Over Its Data Breach and Won
headline.print_headline: How Some People Took Equifax to Small Claims Court and Won

docs.abstract: A number of Your Money readers took Ron Lieber’s advice to freeze their children’s credit. Equifax’s process didn’t always work. Please keep trying.
docs.snippet: A number of Your Money readers took Ron Lieber’s advice to freeze their children’s credit. Equifax’s process didn’t always work. Please keep trying.
docs.lead_paragraph: When the new Equifax chief executive, Mark Begor, appeared before the House Financial Services Committee last week, he put on a brave face and offered conciliatory words.

headline.main: How Equifax Complicates a Simple Task: Freezing a Child’s Credit
headline.print_headline: Making It Complicated To Freeze a Child’s Credit

docs.abstract: The Social Security Administration used to mail out many more statements each year. Now, it encourages workers to go online. A new report says millions haven’t looked.
docs.snippet: The Social Security Administration used to mail out many more statements each year. Now, it encourages workers to go online. A new report says millions haven’t looked.
docs.lead_paragraph: Checking your official Social Security statement is important to make sure your future retirement benefits reflect what you’ve earned over your working life. Yet a new report suggests that many Americans aren’t doing that.

headline.main: Checking on Social Security Estimates Is a Good Idea, but Many People Don’t Do It
headline.print_headline: Why You Should Check Your Social Security Estimate

docs.abstract: The agreement, which calls for the company to pay around $650 million, is meant to resolve federal and state inquiries and consumer claims over the exposure of data of at least 145 million people.
docs.snippet: The agreement, which calls for the company to pay around $650 million, is meant to resolve federal and state inquiries and consumer claims over the exposure of data of at least 145 million people.
docs.lead_paragraph: The credit bureau Equifax is expected to pay around $650 million to settle federal and state investigations and consumer claims relating to a data breach that exposed sensitive information belonging to at least 145 million people, according to two people familiar with the settlement discussions.

headline.main: Equifax Is Said to Be Close to Reaching Deal in Huge ’17 Data Breach
headline.print_headline: $650 Million Deal Likely For Equifax Data Breach

byline.original: By Stacy Cowley and Peter Eavis
